 reviews the idea that magnetic field lines can sometimes terminate or originate
 on singular points.
 More interestingly, magnetic field lines can be made to wrap around a torus
 with irrational winding ratio, so that a single magnetic field line becomes
 dense in the torus, as it wraps around! References papers that talk about
 chaotic magnetic fields, and the ubiquity of singular points in such cases.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
My imagination kicks in.
 In algebraic geometry (e.g.
 Riemann surfaces) singular points are called 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Divisors"
target "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Divisor_(algebraic_geometry)"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and so can we amploy the mechanics of divisors to capture (and completely
 describe) the resulting chaotic field lines? That is, can we say that the
 chaotic field lines are completely describable by saying 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

there is a singular point here, here and here, and everything is irrotational
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

? That is, chaotic motion is normally described by geodesics, and statements
 about the Lyapunov divergence of nearby geodesics.
 Can this be replaced by a global description that enumerates a set of singular
 points?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The case is interesting, because it uses curl (in 3D) or Hodge star and
